			<name>
				<baseName xml:lang="en">Deactivation of active aluminum components ; Bauxite ; Ball mill ; Secondary aluminum slag</baseName>
				<baseName xml:lang="zh">活性铝成分失活 ; 铝土矿 ; 球磨 ; 二次铝渣</baseName>
			</name>
			<classificationInformation>
				<common:classification>
					<common:class level="0">Unit processes</common:class>
					<common:class level="1">Materials production</common:class>
					<common:class level="2">Non-energetic raw materials</common:class>
				</common:classification>
			</classificationInformation>
			<common:generalComment xml:lang="zh">The parameters such as temperature and yield of these three processes were based on experimental results. Life cycle inventory data were from the average data of aluminum industries in China and calculation based on material balance. The electricity type in this study was coal based, which is in line with the actual situation of China’s aluminum industry.      The metal aluminum in secondary aluminum dross (SAD) can be recovered until 1 wt % is left through grinding and sieving. Chlorides in the solution were recovered through concentration and crystallization. Calcium chloride was used to remove fluoride. Ammonia was absorbed by sulfuric acid and used to produce ammonium sulfate. Ball milling was used to promote the direct reaction between active aluminum components and water. Therefore, the ball milling scenario avoided the use of acid or alkali and achieved the deactivation of SAD, except for the use of sulfuric acid to absorb the ammonia generated during the ball milling process. Alumina and other metal oxide (mainly basic oxide) remained in the dross, making the composition and content close to bauxite-like. Therefore, all remaining dross were reused as bauxite-like in the aluminum industry, without any solid waste generated in the ball milling scenario. In this scenario, the deactivation effect of the active aluminum component was about 95%.</common:generalComment>
		</dataSetInformation>
